Contributed for the female bird song project: femalebirdsong.org. CAPTIVE FEMALE. Recording of a captive-bred female in the Rotterdam Zoo, housed in an indoor community aviary together with a male, as well as other species of tropical bird. Individual was in sight during recording and positively identified as the source of the audio. Male and female were told apart using their dimorphic appearance, double-checked by a keeper. Singing happened in the evening, as the sun was setting. Multiple short, loud vocalisations, made from on top of an artifical tree trunk (ca. 3 meters from the ground). It can be told apart from the other species heard (Scissirostrum dubium) as it is the bird singing at 00:00 - 00:09, 00:11 - 00:13, 00:32, 00:55 - 01:00. Possible male response at 0:34, though I didnt hear this sound at the time of recording so that's unsure. Apart from an upright posture no clear display behavior, nor was the male present or vocalising at the onset of the singing. The fragment is not edited. .wav version available on https://ebird.org/checklist/S94650137

CAPTIVE MALE. Recording of a captive-bred male in the Rotterdam Zoo, housed in an indoor community aviary together with a female (not heard or seen at moment of recording), as well as other species of tropical bird. Individual was in sight during recording and positively identified as the source of the audio. Singing happened in the morning, when the sprinklers came on as per routine (which is why there's such noticable background 'static'). Beak was shut for the duration of the song and volume was relatively low. It can be told apart from the other species heard as it is the only song that continues for the length of the recording. Apart from slightly puffed up chest feathers no clear display. The male was perched on a branch, roughly 1,80 meters from the ground. The fragment is not edited. .wav version available on https://ebird.org/checklist/S94649102
